<h1><font size="5">Signal Transduction Pathways Soluble Guanylyl Cyclase</font></h1>
This research focuses on signal transduction and more precisely, on unraveling the pathways that involve the two major second messengers, <b>cyclic adenosine monophosphate</b>
(<b>cAMP</b>) and <b>cyclic guanosine monophosphate</b> (<b>cGMP</b>), and on understanding the mechanisms of modulation of <b>soluble guanylyl cyclase</b> (<b>sGC</b>), a heme containing
enzyme that produces <b>cGMP</b> in response to activation by nitric oxide (<b>NO</b>).
<br><Br>
Physiologically, the <b>NO-cGMP</b> signaling pathway is critically involved in vascular homeostasis via smooth muscle relaxation, in inhibition of platelet aggregation, and in synaptic plasticity
in the nervous system.  Pathophysiologically, dysfunction of this pathway is involved in the development of atherosclerosis, hypercholesterolemia, hypertension, erectile dysfunction and diabetes
mellitus, which are characterized by impairment in vascular reactivity as well as neuropsychiatric disorders and retinal degeneration.
<br><Br>
Almost two decades after <b>NO</b> was identified as the ligand for <b>sGC</b> activation, the mechanism for activation of <b>sGC</b> by <b>NO</b>and other compounds remains unclear,
and the link between <b>NO</b> tolerance and desensitization of <b>sGC</b> is still intensely debated.
<br><Br>
<b>sGC</b> is a heterodimer multi-domain signaling enzyme that contains the receptor-heme domain as shown below
<center>
<br>
<img src="http://sirius2.umdnj.edu/~rossiar/images/hnox.png" width="400" height="400" alt="sGC: A Heterodimer Multi-domain Signaling Enzyme">
<br>
</center>
The challenges involve the determination of the mechanism by which the signal, subsequent to <b>NO</b> binding, is transmitted from the receptor domain (heme binding domain) to the effector
domain (catalytic domain) and the manner in which this transmission is effected in desensitization.
<br><Br>
An understanding of the structural and molecular basis for the  mechanism of regulation by <b>sGC</b> is sought by addressing three crucial questions:
<ol>
<b>
<li>How is the <b>NO</b> signal transmitted from the receptor-heme domain to the catalytic-effector domain?
<li>How does <b>sGC</b> become unresponsive to <b>NO</b> following prolonge exposure or oxidative stress?
<li>Do endogenous modulators of <b>sGC</b> activity play a role in desensitization?
</b>
</ol>
Understanding the mechanism of regulation by <b>sGC</b> and identifying regulatory molecules will be key to uncovering the molecular basis for developing compensatory therapies
for some types of hypertension, atherosclerosis, erectile dysfunction and neurological disorders which affect million Americans.
<br><Br>
<h1><font size="3">Activation of sGC by Nitric Oxide (NO)</font></h1>
One basic problem entails understanding the activation of <b>sGC</b> by the NO. There are varying ideas on the mechanism: Does the NO react with an adjacent cysteinyl residue to form an S-nitrosothiol?;
Does the NO bind to the HEME first to form a rigid template and then react with the cysteine?  Does the NO directly bond to the cysteine? Are two NOs ineeded to allow the mechanism for activation?
<br><Br>
Scientists working on this project include Professor Annie Beuve, Department of Pharmacology and Physiology - UMDNJ, Professor Focco van den Akker, Department of Biochemistry, Case Western Reserve University,
and myself who is performing simulations which can validate the structural predictions/models of <b>sGC</b> and provide an explanation for the mechanism for signal transduction between the three domains of <b>sGC</b>.
